Cornwall, England":"Boscastle, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clinton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Louth, Westmeath) and Scottish: shortened form of   McClinton  .","English: habitational name, either from Glympton in Oxfordshire, named as ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) on the Glym river’, a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright stream’, or from Glinton in Northamptonshire, early recorded as <i>Clinton</i> (named with an unrecorded Old English element akin to Middle Low German <i>glinde</i> ‘enclosure, fence’ + Old English <i>tūn</i>). The surname was taken to Ireland in or before the 16th century.","History: Charles Clinton (born 1690 in Longford, Ireland) organized a group of colonists and founded the settlement of Little Britain, Ulster County, NY, in 1731. His son George Clinton (1739–1812) was governor of NY (1777–95), and they had many prominent descendants. — An English aristocratic family called <i>Clinton</i> was founded by Geoffrey de Clinton (flourished 1130), who held lands at Glympton, Oxfordshire. He was chamberlain and treasurer to Henry I (1100–35)."],"variants":[{"name":"McClinton","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Fhionntain</b> (Scottish), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntáin</b> (Irish) ‘son of the servant (i.e. devotee) of (Saint) <i>Fionntan</i>’, whose name has been explained as ‘the white ancient’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":45,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Clinton was born in 1410, in Whiston, Northamptonshire, England, his father, William Clinton 4th Lord of Maxtock, was 33 and his mother, Lady Anne Botreaux, was 27. He married Joan de Ferrers on 29 October 1431. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 24 September 1464, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1410–24 September 1464":"1410–24. september 1464","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1408–Male":"1408–Surnud","1410–1464":"1410–1464","1410–1483":"1410–1483","1434–1488":"1434–1488","1377–1432":"1377–1432","1383–1420":"1383–1420","29 October 1431":"29. oktoober 1431","1483":"1483","1383":"1383","August 1432":"august 1432","17 October 1420":"17. oktoober 1420","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1377":"1377","1420":"1420","1464":"1464","24 September 1464":"24. september 1464","1408":"1408","1405":"1405","Folkestone, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Folkestone, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whiston, Northamptonshire, England":"Whiston, Northamptonshire, England","Boscastle, Cornwall, England":"Boscastle, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1410–24 September 1464":"1410–24. syyskuuta 1464","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1408–Male":"1408–Kuollut","1410–1464":"1410–1464","1410–1483":"1410–1483","1434–1488":"1434–1488","1377–1432":"1377–1432","1383–1420":"1383–1420","29 October 1431":"29. lokakuuta 1431","1483":"1483","1383":"1383","August 1432":"elokuu 1432","17 October 1420":"17. lokakuuta 1420","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1377":"1377","1420":"1420","1464":"146